50|$|The red form of HgO {{can be made}} by heating Hg in oxygen {{at roughly}} 350 °C, or by {{pyrolysis}} of <b>Hg(NO3)2.</b> The yellow form can be obtained by precipitation of aqueous Hg2+ with alkali. The difference in color is due to particle size, both forms have the same structure consisting of near linear O-Hg-O units linked in zigzag chains with an Hg-O-Hg angle of 108°.|$|E

